calculate center¶

since the stars are only formed in the zoom-region a good first approach to calculate the center of the halo is to compute the center using shinking sphere method implemented in the function nbe.real_center() using the positions and mass of the stars particles.

In [18]:
center = nbe.real_center(myhalo.st.pos3d, myhalo.st.mass)
print("center--> [x y z] =",center," [kpc]")

center--> [x y z] = [14314.92184042 15227.63864653 15696.15744377]  [kpc]

we can shift the coordinate system of the whole simulation to be centered in center using the function myhalo.center_shift(center)

In [19]:
myhalo.center_shift(center)

and, finally, we can calculate the virial radius of the galaxy using the funcion myhalo.r_virial().

Notes:

1) this function not only calculates the virial radius but also also erases all data that is farder than n times the final virial radius from the center. This is done to free memory in case of high resolution simulations. the default value of n incase is not explicitely define is n=2.5.
2) if the virial radius is not found inside a limit radius, r_max, the procedure will stop at 600 kpc unless a different r_max is specified
3) the galaxy will be rotated to have the disc plane in the x-y plane unless the rotate keyword is set to False as in the following example.

In [26]:
myhalo.r_virial(r_max=600,n=2.5,rotate=False)


print("r200 = {0:.2f} kpc".format(myhalo.r200))
